Twitter Sentiment Analysis¶

  • In this module we will be running sentiment analysis on tweets. At UChicago we have the entire tweet corpus which has information pertaining to all the tweets, which are being scraped. In this module I segregate UChicago and NUs tweets to understand how and what the crowd sentiment is towards the two schools
  • We will check what the majority of the audience is tweeting about when it comes to these two schools
  • We will map the tweets as per the location and then see where the tweets are coming from throughout the globe
  • We will do some basic topic modelling to segregate the tweets into different types

In this module I have already segregated the tweets related to UChicago and NU using various hashtags and then after some data cleaning I am using that data set for the anlaysis

Please check the other module which has been used to obtain these tweets.

Note: the column names are fairly intuitive to understand

In [100]:
# Define the projection, scale, the corners of the map, and the resolution.
m = Basemap(projection='merc',llcrnrlat=-80,urcrnrlat=80,\
            llcrnrlon=-180,urcrnrlon=180,lat_ts=20,resolution='c')
# Draw the coastlines
m.drawcoastlines()
# Color the continents
m.fillcontinents(color='coral',lake_color='aqua')
# draw parallels and meridians.
m.drawparallels(np.arange(-90.,91.,30.))
m.drawmeridians(np.arange(-180.,181.,60.))
# fill in the oceans
m.drawmapboundary(fill_color='aqua')
plt.title("Tweet Locations for UChicago")
# This is the step that transforms the data into the map's projection
x,y = m(lat, lon)
#adding on the colors to the map as per the number of tweets received from a particular place

m.plot(x,y, 'bo', markersize=5)
plt.show()

Cleaning the data to process and use for building inferences¶

  • Stemming: Stemming is a rudimentary rule-based process of stripping the suffixes (ing, ly, es, s etc) from a word.
  • Lemmatization: Lemmatization, on the other hand, is an organized & step by step procedure of obtaining the root form of the word, it makes use of vocabulary (dictionary importance of words) and morphological analysis (word structure and grammar relations).

from nltk.corpus import stopwords 
from nltk.stem.wordnet import WordNetLemmatizer
import string
In [45]:
stop = set(stopwords.words('english'))
exclude = set(string.punctuation) 
lemma = WordNetLemmatizer()
def clean(doc):
    stop_free = " ".join([i for i in doc.lower().split() if i not in stop])
    punc_free = ''.join(ch for ch in stop_free if ch not in exclude)
    normalized = " ".join(lemma.lemmatize(word) for word in punc_free.split())
    return normalized
In [46]:
UC_tweets_process = [clean(doc).split() for doc in UC_tweets]
In [47]:
NU_tweets_process=[clean(doc).split() for doc in NU_tweets]

Checking Topic Modeling¶

Topic modeling is a process of automatically identifying the topics present in a text corpus, it derives the hidden patterns among the words in the corpus in an unsupervised manner. Topics are defined as a repeating pattern of co-occurring terms in a corpus. A good topic model results in health, doctor, patient, hospital for a topic Healthcare, and farm, crops, wheat for a topic Farming.

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is the most popular topic modelling technique, Following is the code to implement topic modeling using LDA in python. For a detailed explanation about its working and implementation.

def text_to_vector(text): 
    words = text.split() 
    return Counter(words)

def cosine_similarity():
    num_total=0
    deno_total=0
    #vec1=numeric()
    #vec2=numeric()
    for i in range(10):
        #vector[i]=text_to_vector(UC_tweet_list[i])
        vec1 = text_to_vector(UC_tweet_list[i])
        for j in range(iter_no-1):
            #vector_2[j+1]=)
            vec2 = text_to_vector(UC_tweet_list[j+1])
        
            common = set(vec1.keys()) & set(vec2.keys())
            numerator = sum([vec1[x] * vec2[x] for x in common])
            num_total +=numerator
        
            sum1 = sum([vec1[x]**2 for x in vec1.keys()])
            sum2 = sum([vec2[x]**2 for x in vec2.keys()]) 
            denominator = math.sqrt(sum1) * math.sqrt(sum2)
            deno_total +=denominator
   
    if not deno_total:
        return 0.0 
    else:
        return float(num_total) / deno_total
